Zero-Integration Onboarding

Enterprise software normally dies because integration takes 3–12 months.
Your SaaS wins by making onboarding take 1–2 hours.

The key idea:

Let the AI learn the company’s supply chain automatically instead of forcing manual setup.

⸻

How Zero-Integration Onboarding Works

1. Connect the Email Inbox

Most supply chain communication happens through email anyway.

Companies just connect:
	•	orders@company.com
	•	logistics@company.com
	•	purchasing@company.com

The AI reads historical threads.

It automatically extracts:
	•	suppliers
	•	customers
	•	SKUs
	•	quantities
	•	shipping addresses
	•	carrier names

Within minutes it builds a supply chain map.

⸻

2. AI Document Parsing

Supply chains run on documents like:
	•	Purchase Orders (PO)
	•	Invoices
	•	Bills of Lading
	•	Packing lists
	•	shipping confirmations

Companies upload a few examples.

The AI learns the format automatically.

Example:

PO #38291
SKU: AX-203
Qty: 450
Ship to: Dallas

Even if the format changes per customer, the AI can still parse it.

⸻

3. Spreadsheet Sync

Many companies track inventory or orders in spreadsheets.

Instead of forcing a database integration:

They just connect:
	•	Google Sheets
	•	Excel uploads
	•	CSV files

AI maps the columns automatically.

Example:

Column A → SKU
Column B → Quantity
Column C → Ship Date


⸻

4. AI Relationship Mapping

The system automatically detects:

Company A buys from Company B
Company B ships via Carrier C
Carrier C delivers to Warehouse D

This becomes the supply chain graph.

Companies don’t need to configure it.

⸻

5. Passive Mode (Very Important)

At first the AI just observes.

It doesn’t make changes.

It shows insights like:

Shipment delayed
Invoice mismatch
Inventory shortage risk

Once users trust it, they enable automation.

